{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17822"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.19,0.35,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116730"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10536"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9890"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24600"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116730"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring normal quiet breathing at rest, various pressure changes occur within the thoracic cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between intrapulmonary and intrapleural pressures during normal inspiration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Both pressures become more negative","Intrapulmonary pressure becomes positive while intrapleural pressure becomes negative","Intrapulmonary pressure becomes negative while intrapleural pressure becomes positive","Both pressures remain unchanged","Both pressures become positive"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring normal inspiration, the contraction of the diaphragm and external intercostal muscles expands the thoracic cavity. This expansion causes the intrapleural pressure to become more negative (dropping from approximately -5 cmH\u2082O to -8 cmH\u2082O). The resulting increase in the transpulmonary pressure gradient (the difference between intrapulmonary and intrapleural pressure) causes the lungs to expand. As the lungs expand, the intrapulmonary pressure drops slightly below atmospheric pressure (to about -1 cmH\u2082O), creating a pressure gradient that drives air into the lungs. Therefore, during inspiration, \u003Cstrong\u003Eboth pressures become more negative\u003C/strong\u003E relative to their resting state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive intrapulmonary pressure would cause air to flow out of the lungs, which is characteristic of expiration, not inspiration. A positive intrapleural pressure is abnormal and would lead to lung collapse (pneumothorax) rather than expansion. If both pressures were to become positive, this would oppose lung inflation and prevent air from entering. Similarly, if the pressures remained unchanged, there would be no gradient to drive airflow, and breathing would not occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe negative intrapulmonary pressure creates the pressure gradient that drives air flow into the lungs, while the negative intrapleural pressure maintains lung inflation and prevents collapse.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intrapleural pressure is always negative during normal breathing, becoming more negative during inspiration.","Intrapulmonary pressure fluctuates between negative during inspiration and positive during expiration.","The pressure gradient between intrapulmonary and intrapleural spaces determines lung inflation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 7; p. 125."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:42:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:42:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10536"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116730"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty